[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/1879-in-baseball] Inter-league playoff: Providence Grays (NL) defeat Albany Blues (NA), 2 games to 0.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] A native of Brooklyn, Ferguson played for two of New York's earliest semi-professional clubs in the late 1860s and early 1870s, the Atlantics and Mutuals.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] He is credited with being the first player to bat from both sides of home plate, known as switch-hitting, but the practice was not popular at first.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Among the explanations for this, it is claimed that, due to his personality, players did not want to emulate him.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] In 1871, Ferguson took over the Mutual team as the player-manager.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] In 33 games, he batted .241, while the team finished with a 16–17 record, which put them in fifth place at the season's end.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] As manager, Ferguson insisted upon implicit obedience from his men, but was forced to leave following the season due to heavy rumors of gambling surrounding the team.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] For the 1872 season, Ferguson re-joined his Atlantics team, which was now a member of the National Association as well, and he would stay there through the 1874 season.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] In 1872, he was elected by the players to be the president of the National Association, an office he held through the 1875 season, the last season of the Association.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] On September 1, 1872, Ferguson arranged a benefit game for Al Thake, a 22-year-old left fielder for the Atlantics, who drowned during a fishing trip off Fort Hamilton, in New York Harbor.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] The old Brooklyn Atlantics and Members of the 1869 Cincinnati Red Stockings played against each other in the benefit game.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] While serving as a substitute umpire during a game between the Baltimore Canaries and Mutuals on July 24, 1873, Ferguson received continuous, loud, verbal abuse from Mutuals catcher Nat Hicks.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson and Hicks got into an altercation at the conclusion of the game, which Ferguson ended by hitting Hicks in the left arm with a bat, breaking his arm in two places.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson required a police escort to leave the playing field, and Hicks refused to press charges and the two reconciled afterwards.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] During the final season of the Association, he played and managed the Hartford Dark Blues.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] When the Association dissolved, his Hartford team was accepted into the National League for its inaugural season in 1876, and Ferguson became a League Director.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] As a league official, he was involved in a landmark decision that season.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] The case involved Jim Devlin, pitcher for the Louisville Grays.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Devlin wanted to be released from his contract, claiming that Louisville had failed to fulfill the terms of his contract.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Surrounding Devlin were rumors that he took money from gamblers to throw games, known in the day as "hippodroming".
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson, along with fellow league directors, ruled in favor of the Grays' vice-president Charles Chase, and Devlin was ordered to remain with the Grays.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] The following season, Devlin and three other teammates, SS/2B Bill Craver, OF George Hall and 3B Al Nichols would receive life suspensions for throwing games.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Devlin attempted to gain reinstatement for a number of years, but this was never granted.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] The Dark Blues had turned to Ferguson to play for and manage the team because of his reputation as the most authoritarian captain in the game.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] He was an honest and upstanding citizen in a time when not many ballplayers could say the same.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] However, he was also a domineering, dictatorial captain with a violent streak.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Team discipline did improve in his first season, but his overbearing ways proved divisive, causing the team to bicker amongst themselves.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson's temper would flare up often, even when the team was winning.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Shortstop Tom Carey and center fielder Jack Remsen did not hesitate to yell back, while Burdock and pitcher Candy Cummings, on the other hand, often sulked.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] The situation in Hartford came to a head after a tough loss to the Red Stockings, a game in which Ferguson had committed several errors.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Hartford's main pitcher, Tommy Bond, suggested that Ferguson was "crooked".
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson denied the charge, and Bond quickly retracted his statement, claiming that he said it in anger.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Bond then requested that he be able to leave the team because he could not play for Ferguson, a request that was granted by league president Morgan Bulkeley, a former owner of the Dark Blues.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Hartford finished third in both of its two seasons in the National League, and when the team folded, Ferguson became the new Chicago White Stockings player-manager.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Al Spalding had hired Ferguson to captain his Chicago team because of his reputation, openly saying that he admired Ferguson's style and leadership that made the Hartford teams successful.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson personally had his most successful season as a player that season, as he batted .351, which was third in the league, led the league in on-base percentage, tied for fourth in runs batted in, and ranked fourth in hits.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Unfortunately, the White Stockings finished at .500, and in Spalding's memoirs he called Ferguson "tactless" and hopelessly lacking any knowledge "of the subtle science of handling men by strategy rather than by force." Cap Anson would eventually take over that role in 1879.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson again moved on, this time accepting the player-manager role with the new Troy Trojans team who began their time in the National League in 1879, and would stay in that role until the team folded after the 1882 season.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] In 1883, he became the first manager in the history of the Philadelphia Phillies franchise, which was known at the time as the Quakers, but was relieved of command when the team won only four of its first 17 games.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] On August 21 of that season, his Quakers traveled to Providence, Rhode Island to play the Grays.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] To increase ticket sales, he gave the day's pitching duty to Rhode Island native Art Hagan in hopes that Hagan's appearance would attract more locals to come watch the game.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] The strategy worked, but Hagen surrendered 28 runs and the Quakers made 20 errors behind him and did not score a run.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Financially sound decision as it was, a bad decision for public relations as Ferguson was labeled a sadist for not relieving Hagen.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson's last two managerial positions were in the American Association.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] He was player-manager for the Pittsburgh Alleghenys, who later became the Pittsburgh Pirates, in 1884 and later took over the managerial role for parts of two seasons with the New York Metropolitans.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] As manager in baseball for 933 games, his teams won 417 games and lost 516, for a winning percentage of .447, and never finished higher than the third-place finishes his Trojans achieved.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] The totals reflect his time in the National Association as well as the National League and American Association.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson is just one of two 19th-century managers to have managed for sixteen seasons, but he holds the distinction of having the most seasons managed to neither win 1,000 games nor manage for 1,000.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson had, on numerous occasions during his playing and managerial career, served as a substitute umpire, but did not start doing it full-time until after his departure from Philadelphia.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] In 1888, he became a full-time professional umpire, working in the American Association, and later in the Players' League in 1890.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] By the end of the 1890 season he had passed Kick Kelly to take over the record for career games as an umpire with 650; John Gaffney surpassed his final total of 786 in 1893.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson officially umpired 804 games if his National Association games are taken into account, and his career came to a close after the 1891 season.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] On his umpiring philosophy, he once stated "Umpiring always came as easy to me", he said, "as sleeping on a featherbed.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Never change a decision, never stop to talk to a man.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Ferguson died in Brooklyn of apoplexy at the age of 49.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Initially buried in the Cemetery of the Evergreens in Brooklyn, he was later reinterred in Cypress Hills Cemetery, also in the borough of Brooklyn.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Despite his career that was filled with incidents of turmoil between him and his players and other baseball people, his funeral, which was held at his home, was quickly crowded, as was the front stoop.
[src:bob-ferguson-infielder/bob-ferguson-infielder] Eventually, they had to turn people away.
